{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hine_ver02/data/sn82016181/00529046066/1929111901/0379.xml":{"full_text":"HOME\nEdition\n2 CENTS\nServed by Four Trunk Wires of United Press\u2014World\u2019s Greatest Evening Press Association\nW EA FHER\nFair and shght\n1) colder tonight\nand W ednesday\nlowest tempera\ntine about 36\nvtoter 9th Year\u2014No. 10\nESRipe -WOWARD _\nWASHINGTON, 1. C.,\nTUESDAY\n1929\nREP. DENISON INDICTED ON RUM\nCHARGE BY D. C. GRAND JURY\nNation\u2019s Leading, Railway Executives Confer With President\nh m .._\nFRED W. SARGENT\nChamber of Commerce\nW. W. ATTERBURY\nPennsylvania R. it.\nChesapeake Ohio\nDANIEL W111 Al l)\nBaltimore Ohio\nP E. CROW 1.1 Y\nNew York Central\nRail Leaders Agree\non Expansion Plan\nto Bolster Business\nEastern Heads Who Met With\nHoover Promise to Place Pro\ngram Before Chicago Meet\nHeads of practically all importan\neastern railroads today pledged per\nsonally to President Hoove r to go\nahead with their full construction\nand expansion programs without re\ngard to stock market conditions.\nThis was the first major develop\nment in President Hoover\u2019s effort to\nstimulate confidence in the immedi\nate business outlook. Kailroads are\namong the heaviest buyers of steel\nand their pledge to go ahead with\ntheir orders insures work for steel\nmills, shops, and thousands of em\nployes.\nReserve Board Meeting\nMeantime, the Federal Reserve\nBoard was in session with its ad\nvisory council of bankers from all\nparts of the country who will confer\nwith President Hoover this after\nnoon in the second of the series of\nheart-to-heart talks with business\ngroups which Hoover has scheduled.\nThe decision of the eastern rail\nroad executives will be placed before\nthe general meeting of all rail heads\nat Chicago Friday. Tho the action\nat Chicago cannot be forecast it was\nanticipated here that the lead of the\neastern roads would be followed.\nPrepare Statement\nThe following statement was pre\npared jointly by those participating\nin the conference:\n\"The railway presidents were\nunanimous in their determination to\nco-operate in the maintenance of em\nployment and business progress.\n\"It was stated that the railways\nrepresented would proceed with full\nprograms of construction and better\nment without any reference to recent\nStock Exchange fluctuations; that\nthey would canvass the situation as\nto further possibilities of expansion,\nand that amongst these particular\nrailways it appeared that the total\nvolume of such construction work\nalready indicated an increase during\nthe next six months over the similar\nperiod of last year\nWant Full Program\n\"It was agreed that the whole\nquestion should be taken up at the\nmeeting of the railway executives:\n(Turn to Back Page)\nBOWIE\n*TUsp\u2014Chattabcoet 116 W\nKu. $18.20, $6.30, S3.70 Eulid, 11*\nJ. Scharfer $3.70. $2+0 Mi-nfire 111\nR. Lishman. S3 to. Time 114.\n(First Chart on Sport Page)\nMcPherson Inquiry\nDraws Near Close;\nMay End Thursday\nJoseph Lewark, Street Car Con\nductor, Is the Only Impor\ntant Witness Still to Be Heard\nThe second grand jury investiga\ntion of the McPherson case is draw\ning to a close.\nOf the 25 or 30 witnesses remain\ning to be heard, only the testimony\nof Joseph T. Lewark, conductor on a\nGeorgia-av \u201cowl\u2019\u2019 car the night Mrs.\nVirginia McPherson died, is consid\nered vital.\nThe first witnesses called today\nwere friends of young McPherson\nwho testified that they rode in an\nauto with him to Mt. Rainier the\ni night his wife died. They told the\njury that McPherson and his aunt,\nMrs. Donald McPherson, took sev\neral members of the football team\non which he played out to Mt. Rain\nier. Then went to Mrs. McPherson\u2019s\nhome when they returned, the wit\nnesses said.\nThe jury also called Mr. and Mrs.\nE. Russell Vass, of the Lombardy\n.Apartments. Their apartment faced\nthe McPherson\u2019s. They previously\ntestified that they had noticed a\ntennis ball on a low roof below the\nwindows of the McPherson apart\nmeat on several occasions but that\nthe morning after Mrs. MePher-on\ndied it had disappeared.\nShould the grand jury hear Lew\nark today, the inquiry may come to\nan end by Thursday and Robert A.\nMcPherson Jr., the young widower\nin the District Jail on an \u2018'illegal\u201d\nfirst degree murder indictment, freed\nby the end of the week, providing a\ntrue bill is not returned against him.\nMay Not indict\nThe feeling is growing around the!\ncourt house that no indictment will\nbe returned. Odds of five to two!\nthat McPherson would be indicted, J\nwhich prevailed at the beginning of\nthe hearing, dwindled to three to j\ntwo and finally to even money as the\nhearing progressed.\nThe attitude of Special Prosecutor\nJohn E. Laskey and Thomas F. Cui-\nlen in presenting a chronological pic\nture of all the facts in the case as\nthey occurred, without respect to\nwhether they bore upon the murder\nor suicide theory, indicates that the\njurors are to be left to reach their\nown decision.\nPainstaking Proceedings\nThis departure from the usual\ngrand jury proceeding, where only\nwitnesses having evidence of a pos\n(Turn to Par 31\n1---I\nj Good\u2019s Friend Dies in\nI Preparing for Funeral\nCEDAR RAPIDS, la.- Harry II. I\nLutz, 66, a boyhood chum of .James\nW. Good, Secretary of War, who j\ndied last night at Washington, i\njoined his friend in death today.\nLutz fell dead as he made prep\narations to attend the Hood funer\nal here Friday. He had been in\ngood health until today.\nSoviet Planes Reported\nBombing Chinese Mines\nlly United Fn mm\nH A R B I N Manchuria Soviet j\ntroops attacked the town of Djalain-\nor, Manchuria, and fought a five\nhour battle with Chinesr forces yes\nterday, according i> word received\nhere today.\nCasualties were heavy on both\nsides, with 26 Soviet planes bombing\nChinese coal mines and setting them\nablaze.\nIt was reported that Soviet irreg\nulars held up and robbed the passen\ngers of a train on the Chinee East\nern Railroad and took some of the\npassengers as hostages. 1\nFlags at Half-Staff for\nSecretary flood; Funeral\nServices at White House\nThousands of ilays on public buildings were ordered di. played at\nhalf-staff by President Hoover today as he directed plans for a na\ntional tribute to the memory of the late Secretary of War Good. A\nguard of honor 1 to be post'd later today over the body of the cab\ninet member.\nAll executive departments will be closed tomorrow urtil l p. m., it\nwas announced by Secretary of State Stimson, whose proclamation\nissued under direction of the Pre-jdent -ordered that the flag be di\nplayed at half-taf on all public buildings thruout the U. S. until the\nburial shall have taken place at Crdar Rapids, I i.. Friday noon.\nA committee of -even Senators wa appointed by Vies lrejdent\nCurtis to attend the funeral on behalf of the Senate.\nT\u2019HE unusual honor of a funeral in\nthe White House is to be paid\nSecretary of War .lames W Good,\nwho died at Walter Reed Hospital at\n8:30 last night of complication\nwhich followed an operation last\nWednesday for acute appendicitis.\nThe body of the Cabinet member\nwill be taken tomorrow morning to\nthe White House where, in the Ea-t\nRoom at 11 a. m.. President Hoover,\nOther high government officials and\nmembers of the diplomatic corps will\nattend the last official rites.\nActing Secretary of War l\u2019atrick\nJay Hurley, who was at the hos\npital when death came, is in charge\nof funeral arrangement. He will ae\ncompany the body to Cedar Rapids,\nla., where burial will take place Fri\nday.\nMembers of the Good family, a\nWar Department escort, a represent\nstive from the I\u2019re ident\u2019 cabinet\nprobably Secretary of th Interior\nWilbur, and a deletration from the\nSenate and Hous also will make\nthe trip.\nA sprcial train hearing the body\nand official party is scheduled to\nhave Washington at :15 p. m. to\nmorrow, arriving in Chieago at\na. m. Thursday. From Chicage the\ntrain will move direetly to Cedar\nRapids where it is due late Thur\nday evening.\nMeanwhile, a guard of honor leni I\nis standing ov r the body.\nDeath came aft< r Good, who was;\nC3, had lingered in a semi- on cious\ncondition for more than 21 hour.-', an i\ninsidious pritonitio infection at\nurating the blo d stream. He died\npeacefully, without egaining con\nciousness Only his robust vitality\n(Turn to Page 3)\nRep. Denison and His\nF o r m e r Secretary\nFact* Rum Charges\nIllinois Congressman and John\nLayne Involved in Ownership\nof Liquor Found at Capitol\nRep. Edward E. Denison of Mar\nion, III., and his former secretary,\nJohn Layne, were indicted today by\nthe Hist nit grand jury on charge,\nof posye ssing liquor.\nThe indictment is the result of the\nseizure Jan. 19 by prohibition agents\nat Inion Station of a suitcase al\nleured to have contained liquor, and\na trunk filled with liquor in the\nHouse Oflice Building.\nSent I rom New York\nThe uitease, accordig to the ir\nthietment, was addresed to Layne,\nnow an attorney in the ofliee of the\ngeneral counsel of the Hurau of in\nternal Kevenueg \u2018t w as sent from\nNew lork, in care of Denison at\n11 1 Home Oflice Buildis.g.\nlayne sad tolay that he had not\nI.n Mennison\u2019s secretary for nmne\nyeat., and that the indict metit wa\nthe fir t he had ever henid of the\ncase.\nProhibition apent: informed Dt.\nAtty. Kovr that the suitca beat\ning layne\u2019 name, was shipped on\nan express bill of lading with a\ntrunk. Search of express company\nfile discloptd that the trunk had\nbeen delivered at the time the Milt\nca v. as found.\nThe agents ad it y went to Den\nng on\u2019s office aud there found the\ntrunk. Detm-on was also there, they\naid, and told them that her did not\nhave a ke y to the trunk, but tuat he\nwould get it for tnem later.\nThe agent returned latel and\nwere then told by Deni-on that the\nliquor in the trunk did not le don? to\nhim. He gave them pern -jon to\nbreak open the 